==Abstract==

This IIP describes the OP_CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY (CSV) opcode which allows a transaction output to be made unspendable until a relative time or block count has passed since the output was confirmed. It is adapted from BIP 112 for INTcoin.

==Motivation==

While IIP-7 defines relative lock-time semantics for sequence numbers, script authors need a way to enforce these constraints. OP_CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY provides script-level enforcement, enabling:

* '''Bidirectional Payment Channels''': Revocable outputs with enforced delay
* '''Lightning Network''': HTLC timeout enforcement
* '''Vault Contracts''': Mandatory waiting periods
* '''Inheritance Schemes''': Time-delayed access

==Specification==

===Opcode Definition===

<pre>
OP_CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY = 0xb2
</pre>

When executed:

# If the stack is empty, fail
# If the top stack item is negative, fail
# If the top stack item has the disable flag (bit 31) set, continue without further checks
# If the transaction version is less than 2, fail
# If the input's nSequence has the disable flag set, fail
# If the type flags don't match (stack bit 22 vs nSequence bit 22), fail
# If the stack value (masked) is greater than nSequence (masked), fail
# Otherwise, continue (the stack is not modified)

===Pseudocode===

<pre>
def op_checksequenceverify(stack, tx, input_index):
    if len(stack) < 1:
        return False

    sequence = stack[-1]  # Don't pop

    if sequence < 0:
        return False

    DISABLE_FLAG = 1 << 31
    TYPE_FLAG = 1 << 22
    MASK = 0x0000ffff

    # If disable flag set in script, pass
    if sequence & DISABLE_FLAG:
        return True

    # Require transaction version >= 2
    if tx.nVersion < 2:
        return False

    input_seq = tx.vin[input_index].nSequence

    # If disable flag set in input, fail
    if input_seq & DISABLE_FLAG:
        return False

    # Type flags must match
    if (sequence & TYPE_FLAG) != (input_seq & TYPE_FLAG):
        return False

    # Compare values
    if (sequence & MASK) > (input_seq & MASK):
        return False

    return True
</pre>

===Script Examples===

'''Relative time lock (144 blocks ≈ 288 minutes):'''

<pre>
<144> OP_CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY OP_DROP <pubkey> OP_CHECKSIG_DILITHIUM
</pre>

'''Time-based lock (1 day ≈ 169 units):'''

<pre>
<0x00400000 + 169> OP_CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY OP_DROP <pubkey> OP_CHECKSIG_DILITHIUM
</pre>

'''Revocable output (Lightning commitment):'''

<pre>
OP_IF
    <revocation_pubkey> OP_CHECKSIG_DILITHIUM
OP_ELSE
    <144> OP_CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY OP_DROP
    <local_pubkey> OP_CHECKSIG_DILITHIUM
OP_ENDIF
</pre>

==Rationale==

===Transaction Version Check===

Requiring version >= 2 ensures:
* Old transactions are unaffected
* Clear opt-in to relative lock-time semantics
* Forward compatibility

===Disable Flag in Stack Value===

Allowing the disable flag in the script value:
* Enables conditional CSV (using OP_IF branches)
* Matches nSequence semantics

===Type Flag Matching===

Requiring matching type flags prevents:
* Comparing blocks to time (nonsensical)
* Accidentally satisfying locks with wrong units

==Backwards Compatibility==

OP_CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY was previously OP_NOP3. Scripts using OP_NOP3:
* Continue to work (CSV is a soft fork restriction)
* Now have semantic meaning with appropriate values

==Interaction with Other IIPs==

* '''IIP-6 (CLTV)''': Can combine absolute and relative locks
* '''IIP-7 (Sequence)''': CSV enforces IIP-7 semantics in scripts

Example combining both:

<pre>
<500000> OP_CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY OP_DROP
<144> OP_CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY OP_DROP
<pubkey> OP_CHECKSIG_DILITHIUM
</pre>

This requires:
* Block 500000 to be reached (absolute)
* AND 144 blocks since the UTXO was created (relative)

